              <ol>
                <li>
                  <b>Thermostat</b>
                  <p>
                    The thermostat in a freezer regulates the internal
                    temperature by cycling the compressor on and off to maintain
                    the desired temperature. If the thermostat malfunctions, it
                    might cause the freezer to run continuously or not at all,
                    leading to either excessive frost buildup or thawing of
                    frozen items. Poor temperature regulation can also result in
                    higher energy consumption.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Door Seal/Gasket</b>
                  <p>
                    The door seal, or gasket, creates an airtight barrier
                    between the freezer's interior and the external environment.
                    This prevents warm air from entering and cold air from
                    escaping. A faulty or worn-out gasket can lead to
                    temperature fluctuations, frost buildup, and increased
                    energy usage as the freezer works harder to maintain the set
                    temperature.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Evaporator Fan Motor</b>
                  <p>
                    The evaporator fan motor circulates cold air throughout the
                    freezer, ensuring even cooling. If this motor fails, it can
                    result in uneven temperature distribution, with some areas
                    becoming too warm while others may remain frozen. This can
                    also lead to the compressor overworking, potentially causing
                    further damage to the unit.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Defrost Heater</b>
                  <p>
                    The defrost heater prevents ice build-up on the evaporator
                    coils by melting any accumulated frost during the defrost
                    cycle. If the defrost heater fails, frost can accumulate on
                    the coils, obstructing airflow and reducing the freezerâ€™s
                    efficiency. This can cause the freezer to struggle to
                    maintain the desired temperature
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Compressor</b>
                  <p>
                    The compressor is the heart of the freezer's cooling system,
                    compressing refrigerant and circulating it through the coils
                    to remove heat from inside the unit. A malfunctioning
                    compressor can lead to inadequate cooling or complete
                    failure of the freezer. Replacing a compressor can be costly
                    and sometimes may warrant considering a new freezer.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Start Relay</b>
                  <p>
                    The start relay works with the compressor to help it start
                    and run efficiently. A faulty start relay can prevent the
                    compressor from kicking on, leading to a non-cooling
                    freezer. This component is relatively easy to replace and
                    can resolve issues related to the compressor not starting.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Run Capacitor</b>
                  <p>
                    The run capacitor provides the necessary power boost to
                    start the compressor and keep it running. If the capacitor
                    is defective, the compressor might struggle to start or run
                    inefficiently, causing cooling problems. Similar to the
                    start relay, this is a relatively inexpensive and
                    straightforward part to replace
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Defrost Timer</b>
                  <p>
                    The defrost timer controls the cycle of the defrost heater,
                    ensuring that the freezer defrosts periodically to prevent
                    frost buildup. If the defrost timer malfunctions, it can
                    either cause the freezer to defrost too frequently or not at
                    all, leading to either excessive frost or a warm freezer
                    compartment.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Ice Maker Assembly</b>
                  <p>
                    The ice maker assembly is responsible for producing ice
                    cubes automatically. If the ice maker is defective, it might
                    stop making ice, produce misshapen cubes, or leak water.
                    Issues can arise from a faulty motor, clogged water lines,
                    or malfunctioning sensors within the assembly.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Water Inlet Valve</b>
                  <p>
                    The water inlet valve controls the flow of water into the
                    ice maker and water dispenser. A malfunctioning valve can
                    result in no water flow, leading to the ice maker not
                    producing ice or water dispenser not working. It can also
                    cause leaks if the valve does not shut off properly.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Temperature Control Board</b>
                  <p>
                    The temperature control board manages and regulates the
                    freezerâ€™s temperature settings. A defective control board
                    can lead to inaccurate temperature readings, causing the
                    freezer to run too cold or too warm. This can compromise the
                    preservation of stored food and increase energy consumption.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Thermistor</b>
                  <p>
                    The thermistor senses the temperature inside the freezer and
                    sends this information to the control board. If the
                    thermistor is faulty, it can provide incorrect temperature
                    readings, leading to improper cooling cycles. This can
                    result in the freezer being either too cold or not cold
                    enough.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Door Switch</b>
                  <p>
                    The door switch activates the interior light and may also
                    control the operation of the evaporator fan when the freezer
                    door is opened. A broken door switch can prevent the light
                    from turning on or off and might cause the evaporator fan to
                    run continuously or not at all, affecting cooling
                    performance.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Drain Pan</b>
                  <p>
                    The drain pan collects water that drips off the evaporator
                    coils during the defrost cycle. If the drain pan is cracked
                    or damaged, it can cause water leaks and potential water
                    damage to the surrounding area. Ensuring the drain pan is
                    intact and correctly positioned is crucial for proper
                    freezer maintenance.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Light Bulb</b>
                  <p>
                    The light bulb illuminates the freezer interior when the
                    door is opened. A burned-out bulb does not affect the
                    freezer's cooling performance but can make it inconvenient
                    to find items inside. Replacing the bulb is a simple fix
                    that restores visibility.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Evaporator Coil</b>
                  <p>
                    The evaporator coil absorbs heat from inside the freezer,
                    allowing the refrigerant to evaporate and cool the
                    compartment. If the coil is damaged or covered in frost, it
                    can hinder the cooling process, leading to inefficient
                    operation or complete cooling failure
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Condenser Fan Motor</b>
                  <p>
                    The condenser fan motor helps dissipate heat from the
                    refrigerant by blowing air over the condenser coils. If the
                    fan motor fails, the coils can overheat, reducing the
                    freezer's ability to cool effectively. This can also cause
                    the compressor to overheat and potentially fail.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Shelf or Drawer</b>
                  <p>
                    Shelves and drawers inside the freezer provide organization
                    and maximize storage space. Broken or missing shelves and
                    drawers can reduce storage efficiency and make it difficult
                    to keep items organized. Replacing these parts ensures
                    better use of the freezerâ€™s interior space.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Control Board</b>
                  <p>
                    The control board is the brain of the freezer, managing all
                    functions including temperature regulation, defrost cycles,
                    and user interface. A faulty control board can lead to
                    various issues, such as erratic temperatures,
                    non-functioning displays, or failure of the freezer to run
                    altogether
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Defrost Thermostat</b>
                  <p>
                    The defrost thermostat monitors the temperature of the
                    evaporator coils and ensures that the defrost heater is
                    activated at the correct time to melt any frost buildup. A
                    malfunctioning defrost thermostat can either prevent the
                    defrost cycle from starting, leading to frost accumulation,
                    or cause it to run too long, wasting energy and potentially
                    warming up the freezer.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
